  "body": "\r\n\r\n#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: 1.9.6-unstable\r\nOS & Version: Linux (Debian 10)\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nGeth start syncing after `geth --datadir=/var/local/ethereum` command.\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\n````\r\n$ geth --datadir=/var/local/ethereum\r\nINFO [12-04|18:49:49.795] Bumping default cache on mainnet         provided=1024 updated=4096\r\nINFO [12-04|18:49:49.796] Maximum peer count                       ETH=50 LES=0 total=50\r\nINFO [12-04|18:49:49.796] Smartcard socket not found, disabling    err=\"stat /run/pcscd/pcscd.comm: no such file or directory\"\r\nFatal: Failed to create the protocol stack: mkdir /var/local/ethereum: read-only file system\r\n````\r\n\r\nNote that the directory already exists, so it's weird that geth tried to create it. And it is configured with the loosest permission (in attempt to disapprove \"read-only\").\r\n\r\n````\r\n$ ls -lhd /var/local/ethereum\r\ndrwxrwxrwx 2 root root 4.0K Dec  4 18:43 /var/local/ethereum\r\n````\r\nalso that it is not read-only:\r\n````\r\n$ touch /var/local/ethereum/f\r\n$ ls /var/local/ethereum/f\r\n````\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n\r\n1. Install snapd on Debian 10\r\n2. Use snap to install geth\r\n3. Create /var/local/ethereum with the loosest permission.\r\n4. Run `geth --datadir=/var/local/ethereum`\r\n",
